President Joseph R. Biden Jr. has proclaimed June 2022 as National Caribbean-American Heritage Month in recognition of the immeasurable contributions of Caribbean Americans to the United States. He highlights the strength and diversity brought by immigrants throughout history, and specifically acknowledges the achievements of Vice President Kamala Harris, the first Black American of Jamaican heritage to hold the office. The President also honors other public servants of Caribbean heritage, including Secretary of Education Miguel Cardona, Secretary of Homeland Security Alejandro Mayorkas, and Domestic Policy Advisor Susan Rice. He acknowledges the persistence and character of Caribbean Americans who have fought for equity and equality despite discrimination and hardship. The contributions of Caribbean American entrepreneurs, scientists, medical professionals, teachers, artists, police officers, athletes, and individuals in various fields are recognized. President Biden acknowledges that systemic barriers to success still exist for many Caribbean Americans due to systemic racism and disparities in opportunity. His administration is committed to advancing racial justice and equity to ensure equal access to the American dream for all Americans. The proclamation encourages all Americans to celebrate the history, culture, and achievements of Caribbean Americans through appropriate ceremonies and activities.